segments.text: I'm running than you do in the high hurdles.
And technique is not nearly as important.
What is important is power and speed.
So I got through the Border Olympics.
I won, as I said.
And then we got ready for the Texas Relays.
I busted up my knee on a curb and was in the hospital at the time the Texas Relays came about.
So we get ready for the Kansas relays, which is toward the end of April.
And I'm still nursing a sore knee.
And I qualified for the finals, but I didn't place.
So we go to the Drake relays.
We have a snowstorm.
There's about four to six inches of snow on the ground.
We come out for the preliminaries.
Bob Hall, who's a teammate, Southwest Conference record holder in the low hurdles.
And Billy Bless, teammate, classmate, and I were entered in the low hurdles.
I was also entered in the high hurdles.
This is the first or the second big major outdoor carnival.
And this attracted a lot of schools from the Midwest, an awful lot of them.
I actually placed third in the high hurdles in that.
That was a kind of a junior NCAA type meet.
And I was very pleased with that.

And we had the low hurdles and Bob Hall did not qualify for the finals in the low hurdles because the track was so sloppy from all of that snow and they had tried to broom it off with a rotary broom and then they poured diesel fuel on it and set it on fire.
to try to burn all the moisture out of there.
It just made an absolute mess.
And poor old Bobby, he was too short legged.
He couldn't quite stretch it to that ninth hurdle.
And he hit it and he went tumbling and he was out of the race.
Well, it didn't bother me.
I was, you know, I was like an old mule in mud.
I was getting going.
Come time for the finals, I'm lined up against the
NCAA champion from Notre Dame, Bill Fleming.
Fleming gets the middle lane.
I got the inside lane, which is all chewed up, sloppy, and I have to run more curves than anybody else because I'm on the inside.
Gun went off, I took off, and somehow or other, I got a two-foot lead and held it.
And one of the drake relays
What a nice bull of a watch for him.
And then we went to the conference meet.
And I won the high hurdles in the conference meet and placed third in the load held in Austin that sophomore year.
And I was also, I won the Doc Lipscomb award, MVP award for that year.
Did y'all go to the NCAA then?
I did not.
We sent a team.
Our first child was due at that time.
So I thought it prudent for my own survival that I stay home for that event, and I did.
I did go, however, to the National AAU track meet at College Park, Maryland on the 23rd, 24th, and 25th of June.

1950 and the Beaumont A&M Club and Charlie Babcock paid my way up there and I stayed the first night with Tiger Teague and his wife and young Jack Teague and then the second night I moved out to a dormitory at College Park and I was third in the high hurdles there
up hills of Marin and White.
What was your, you remember what your best time was that year?
Yeah, my best time in high hurdles was 14.5 at the conference meet, and 22, 23 flat in the low hurdles.
Let's sidetrack.
Describe Olin Teague, who was then a young, new member of the U.S. Congress from this district.
That's not easy to do.
I met him.
Mrs. Teague met me at Washington National Airport.
How nice.
And of course he was in committee meetings and Congress was in session.
As a matter of fact, he didn't even make it home for dinner that night.
Now, he was a comparatively small bundle of energy, wasn't he?
Yes, he was.
And boy, he was buzzing around everywhere.
Vivacious.
I just wasn't exposed to him that much.
I spent maybe 10, 15 minutes with him at the moment.
Mrs. Teague was a very gracious lady.
All right.
Your junior and your senior, well, as you're a young married man, did you go on court trips?
Sophomore?
No.
Sophomore, junior, you didn't go on court trips.
But you all went to Silver Taps and to Muster.
Did you go to midnight yell practices?
Yes.
Where were they held?
Midnight yell practice was held.
West side of the Y or the Grove?
They were held on the steps of Goodwin Hall.
Goodwin, OK. And they were not at midnight yet, were they?
No.
They were just called midnight yell practice.
They were held around 9 or 10 o'clock at night.
That's right.
And did the yell leaders tell fables then?
Oh, yes.
They'd get up there and tell great tales of heroics.
And the individual football player would get up there.
And they would tell stories.
But later there would be some of the fables would be off color.
But was that done in your era?
No.
That's what I thought.
That's a new thing.
No.
I've forgotten how Lizzie went.
But it was done in a deep bass voice.
And the punchline was
Son of a gun, Lizzie.
And it was, oh, I remember how it went.
Is my lipstick on straight?
Loan me your comb, sweet cherry phosphate.
Son of a gun, Lizzie.
It was a holdover from World War I in those days.
Now, there was a put-down Aggie yell for every Southwest Conference opponent, wasn't there?
A kind of a spoof?
More of a kush call than a yell.
OK, OK. We, as far as put downs go, no.
The only put down that we had was beat the hell out of them.
OK. Was there, by that point, were Aggies yelling gig'em?
You bet.
Because I understand that way back in the 30s, there was a yell, what do you do with those frogs?
You gig them.
Very likely.
And that Pinky, I understand, deserves credit for kind of taking that.
Gig them, gig them, gig them.
I believe that.
And I do too, given his personality.
And so you and your wife and then your youngster, y'all would go to y'all practices and to bonfire.
We would.
And things like that.
We would.
Let's see.
Getting on to your junior year, how did it go with a young track man?
Well, my junior year, we were finally able to get an apartment.
The Brenham A&M Club had an old World War I barracks building that they had moved about a block behind Southside Grocery, where Rother's Bookstore is now, on Montclair.
And they made it into four apartments, two upstairs, two downstairs.
And there was a bath up and a bath down, and you shared them.
And they were three-room apartments, a bedroom, a living room or study, and a kitchen.
And we thought that was just uptown.
Unfurnished.
Unfurnished.
You had to have your own furniture.
And Betty's mother had a large three-story house, and she had rented out rooms, so that was not a problem.
And her mother and father loaned us that furniture.
Remember what the rent was?
$20 a month, which included the utilities.
There was a telephone, and we all split the telephone bill.
And if you made a long-distance call, then you settled up at the end of the month with Oscar Bockhorn, who was the dorm meister.
And we had a great time.
It was wonderful.
We didn't know we were poor.
We still didn't have a car.
We got around by bicycle.
We had friends who had cars and they were more than generous about inviting us to go with them.
Go to a drive-in movie or go to the Triangle and we would reciprocate whenever we could.
And those were good years, really good years.
It was good academically and athletically.
And you didn't have any severe problem that you had to cope with where you had to turn to Colonel Andy or somebody for advice about what do I do now?
Nobody got badly sick?
No.
No car wrecks?
We were very fortunate and still are to this day.
Alright, so junior year, does it go well athletically?
Junior year went well athletically.
With one exception.
There was a fellow named Val Joe Walker.
He was a football player and a track man.
He was a sprinter.
Val Joe also learned how to hurdle.
He had been a hurdler, but he didn't really know how.
He didn't have the technique.
And somebody got him aside and taught him how to hurdle.
And he started giving me problems.
Oh, was he an Aggie?
No, he was from SMU.
Oh, that's right.
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah.
And he had a deformed left hand.
It looked about like that.
He had no fingers.
But he was one heck of a football player and a good track man, too.
And he and I
traded wins that year.
And I remember sports writers used to try to goad us into saying bad things about each other.
And Battle Joe had run a 14-1 in the high hurdles with the win.
And a sports writer from the Houston Post contacted me
asked me what I thought about that and what my chances are in the Southwest Conference meet.
And I said, well, he's going to have to run 14-1 to beat me.
Well, son of a gun if you didn't do it.
And he knows me out by about two feet.
In the conference?
In the conference meet.
And we had traded wins back and forth in the high and the low hurdles all that year.
And Billy Bless moved up from, all of a sudden he learned how to sprint in the 220.
And I was still going my same speed.
If the track got wet or sloppy, I'd take him.
But on a good dry track, on a good day, he just had too much speed for me.
And he won the conference meet that year in the lows in 23 flat.
And I finished third.
Bobby Joe Ragsdale, who was also a sprinter.
They kept getting these sprinters and teaching them how to hurdle them.
I thought that was unfair.
All right, now by this time, the Korean War was underway.
Do you remember how you heard about the start of the Korean War?
Do you remember?
I was at the National AAU Track Meet at College Park, Maryland, on the 25th of June.
It was about 2 o'clock in the afternoon.
I had just finished the high hurdles, was getting ready to run the low hurdles.
And the PA announcer came on the horn and said, we have a report here that the North Koreans have invaded South Korea, wherever that is, is the way he put it.
He says, that's all we have at this time.
And I thought, oh, boy.
You know, here I am ready to be a junior, ready to get my contract for senior ROTC.
I got a wife and a kid.
And the kid's two weeks, less than two weeks old.
And what's going to happen?
Did you and your buddies talk about those realities then?
Yes, we did.
We certainly did.
And...

we all decided that a few who were borderline academically decided what the heck I'm tired of this and they went ahead and enlisted or whatever and joined the Army, the Navy, the Air Force a lot of them went in the Air Force that seemed to be the service of choice at that time
Now, did the, at that point, do we have officially the Air Force or was it still the old Army Air Corps?
No, it was Air Force.
Okay.
Ever since Truman signed the National Defense Service Act of 47, we've been Air Force.
All right, and so.
We even had the Bulls.
had the new Air Force silver tan uniform.
Of course, we wore the Army pinks and greens.
A beautiful uniform.
Back here at A&M, then, you were in an Air Force company?
No, I was still in B athletics.
Oh, you were still in B athletics.
What led you to decide to seek a contract?
I had a private pilot's license.
I started flying when I was in high school.
Okay.
And I always wanted to fly.
Okay.
And of course the Universal Military Training Act had been voted by Congress in 48 while I was still in high school.
And it was just a foregone conclusion that you were going to go in some branch of the service.
And particularly with the Korean War going on,
I was going to fly airplanes.
And they just got new jets.
And that was where I wanted to be.
And I don't know that my wife ever expressed any misgivings about it.
Everybody accepted that was the way life was going to be.
And you just made the best of the hand you were dealt.
Now you went to summer camp after
Never went to summer camp.
Oh, really?
The class of 52 did not go to summer camp because it was the height of the Korean War.
And the Texas A&M students did not because they figured they're just as good as academy students, or nearly as good.
The academy students didn't think that.
But we did not go to summer camp.
Oh, okay.
So let's go then to your senior year.
Y'all stay in this apartment.
Yes.
And you're still with that same major.
You're still planning to be an insurance man.
Still business, still insurance.
Okay.
And Colonel Andy is still the head coach?
He still is.
Okay.
Did he ever give you, during those four years,
Did he ever give you any clear do's and don'ts?
Don't do this, and you must do this, this, this?
No.
Like, did he ever tell you don't smoke?
No, he left that up to us.
I never heard him say anything about smoking or drinking one way or the other.
He knew that that was going on, and as long as it wasn't a problem,
He didn't choose to make it a problem.
In your era, if we had been able to compare the average grade point score of the track team with the student body at large, how would they have compared, reckon?
Beat the socks off of them.
Is that right?
In my class of 52, six of the top 10
Students were Letterman athletes.
Including you and who else?
Gerald Natardis was the valedictorian.
He was a Letterman and honorable mention in football.
Marvin Atkins was not an athlete.
He was a salutatorian.
I was number three in the class.
I've forgotten who was number four.
Glenn Lippman was number five football player, all Southwest Conference.
Hilo Novovitsa was number six or seven, all Conference guard.
And that's six.
No, no, that's not six.
Trying to think of who the other one was.
I'll think of it in a minute.
As far as you were aware, were there any special grade giveaway courses for athletes?
No.
Not for athletes.
You had Dr. Dan Russell.
Dr. Dan.
Dr. Dan, the grade point man.
If he can't pass you, nobody can.
But that was for anybody that took the course.
Yeah.
You know, if you needed some grade points, you'd go take rural sociology.
Was there, were there any courses that were so tough that everybody was scared to take that course from that?
There was thermodynamics, differential calculus, descriptive geometry.
They would separate the men from the boys.
Were there some courses that everybody took just because they were pleasant, that they were enjoyable?
A few.
I took a course in the New Testament in the spring of my sophomore year because I wanted to learn more about it.
Do you remember who taught it?
No, I don't.
It was an assistant pastor at First Baptist Church up at Northgate.
Classes were held there.
And I took Rural Sociology under Dr. Dan simply because I wanted to find out what it was about.
Now, was it easy to make it?
Exceptionally easy.
It was?
It was almost comical.
It was, well, the title of this particular rural sociology course was Marriage and the Family.
I thought, well, maybe he'll teach me something I don't know that I need.
And it was just your usual SOP stuff.
But everybody loved Dr. Dan.
We need to quit.
Because it's ten minutes to six.
Is it?
I've been yakking for that long.
No, no, no, no.
I'm not, I'm not, don't hear me.
But I need to let you go.
And then, now we're checking, checking, checking to see if it's working today.
Is mine working?
This is now Friday, March 9th.
And we're continuing.

When we left off yesterday, we were getting near the finally important matters, but before we get to those, would you describe some of the very notable athlete individuals that were here during your four years in all the sports?
I'll start with
of those guys.
Who was your closest track team buddy?
My closest track team buddy would have been Buddy Schaefer from El Paso.
Buddy is now a practicing dentist.
He may not be practicing any longer, he may be retired, but he became a dentist and moved back to the El Paso area.
The track team manager, T.K.
Burke, was another very close friend.
T.K.
went into Marine Corps aviation and made a career out of the Marine Corps.
Give some examples of the friendship of you and those guys.
What did you all do together and what did you share and so forth?
We palled around together quite a bit, particularly on track trips.
And an interesting story about Buddy Schaefer, and it has to do with Kyle Roach, Doak Walker, and Harry Stiteman.
SMU was playing us here in 1949.
Buddy Schaefer was a sophomore, and he played substitute halfback and did our kickoff.
Mm-hmm.
And we were tied with SMU, I believe, 14 to 14 and a half.
And Stitler called Schaefer over.
We were going to kick off to SMU.
And of course, Walker and Roach were deep for SMU.
And Stitler told Buddy, he says, Schaefer, whatever you do, don't stick it to Walker.
Okay, Coach, I got you.
So he kicks it to Rope.
Rope takes it on the one-yard line and goes 99 yards for a touchdown.
And Stidler called Schaefer over the sideline and grabbed him by the shoulder pad.
He says, Schaefer, what the hell did you kick it to Rope for?
And he says, Coach, all you told me was not to kick it to Walker.
And eventually we got close to SMU.
But they finally beat us.
And that year, I think we won one game.
I believe it was either Trinity or Texas Tech.
I'm not sure.
And we lost nine.
Other special athletes?
Special in my class, particularly, was Buddy Davis, Walter Davis from Nederland, Texas.
Buddy was 6'10", 6'11", and he high jumped.
And he had been using the scissors method of high jumping, which was not a very efficient method.
And Colonel Andy taught Buddy to do the western row and the barrel row.
The western row you would do kind of on your back, very similar to the Fosbury flop that's in use today.
And he also did the barrel row where he would go over with his chest to the bar.
But he made dramatic improvement from his sophomore year to his junior year after Colonel Andy got him into the western row and barrel row area.
And...
He was a good friend.
I had played basketball against him when he was at Meadland and I was at Walmart High.
As a matter of fact, I scored five straight baskets on him from, yeah, I was playing at the top of the key and I used a fadeaway hook shot without even looking at the basket.
It baffled him and surprised the heck out of me.
I figured I was going to get his
big hand down the back of my neck.
But I was there at SMU in 1952 at Only Field when Buddy set a new world record for about 20 or 30 minutes.
And one of the rules of the course was that there could not be more than one half of an inch variation in the takeoff apron
in front of the bar.
And they found one edge way out on the fringe that wasn't being used that was about an inch higher than the bar.
And they couldn't submit it for a record.
So it went from seven feet down to I think it was 6'11".
The world record at that time was 6'11 12".
But Buddy eventually got the record

later on and of course he won the olympic games that year in 52. yes now was he a classmate yes so he he won the olympics in the summer after he graduated that's correct it was in helsinki he and dara hooper represented texas a&m and the united states and dara hooper finished second in the shot to perry o'brien he and perry dueled
throughout their collegiate careers.
And Perry always came out about one or two inches ahead of Darrow, but Darrow was a real competitor and a good friend.
Now, Darrow was from Fort Worth?
He was from Northside, Fort Worth.
A stater.
And he and his young bride, he married at the tail end of, I believe, between his freshman year and his sophomore year.
His wife and Betty and I piled around together quite a bit, and we had a great time.
They were good friends.
Now, Darragh, did he play football also?
Yes, he did.
He came out of Northside-Fort Worth as a quarterback.
He was a big, tall guy.
He was 6'3", and he weighed about 215 or 220.
Beautifully built man, and of course, when he got here,
He was a little bit out of his league as far as the quarterback was concerned.
But they made an end out of him, and he could shag good pass, play good defense, and more importantly, he was a place kicker.
And he kicked the field goal that beat Texas here in 1951.
That kind of thing.
Let's see, other athletes.
Some of the other athletes, some of the upperclassmen
of note and good friends, George Cadera, who was a white man.
